1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:01,333
At T plus zero point six seven eight

2
00:00:01,333 --> 00:00:04,884
seconds, the first warning appeared.

3
00:00:05,585 --> 00:00:07,755
It was smoke from the aft field joint

4
00:00:07,755 --> 00:00:10,358
of Challenger's right solid rocket booster.

5
00:00:11,300 --> 00:00:13,770
More smoke followed through the first two and

6
00:00:13,770 --> 00:00:15,070
a half seconds of flight.

7
00:00:15,070 --> 00:00:18,076
Then it stopped. For the next minute,

8
00:00:18,076 --> 00:00:20,140
Challenger looked like a launch.

9
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:22,885
The vehicle climbed. The callouts continued.

10
00:00:23,506 --> 00:00:25,333
The machinery of the mission appeared to be

11
00:00:25,333 --> 00:00:26,551
doing what it had done before.

12
00:00:27,353 --> 00:00:29,056
But the accident had already begun.

13
00:00:29,818 --> 00:00:32,566
The visible catastrophe came later,

14
00:00:32,566 --> 00:00:34,948
about seventy-three seconds after liftoff.

15
00:00:34,968 --> 00:00:37,248
By then the public version could be told

16
00:00:37,248 --> 00:00:40,045
quickly: it was cold, the O-rings failed,

17
00:00:40,045 --> 00:00:42,279
and seven crew members died.

18
00:00:43,020 --> 00:00:44,140
That version is accurate.

19
00:00:44,921 --> 00:00:46,729
It is also too small to explain why

20
00:00:46,729 --> 00:00:48,085
launch was still allowed.

21
00:00:49,167 --> 00:00:51,188
The smoke is the better starting point because

22
00:00:51,188 --> 00:00:53,313
it separates the consequence from the beginning.

23
00:00:54,213 --> 00:00:56,597
At seventy-three seconds, the chain became public.

24
00:00:57,317 --> 00:00:58,601
At less than one second,

25
00:00:58,601 --> 00:01:00,262
the chain became physical.

26
00:01:01,042 --> 00:01:03,105
Before that, the chain had already been

27
00:01:03,105 --> 00:01:05,635
organizational. The harder question starts before

28
00:01:05,635 --> 00:01:09,272
ignition: how does a warning stay visible in

29
00:01:09,272 --> 00:01:12,817
records, inspections, memos, charts, and meetings,

30
00:01:12,817 --> 00:01:16,008
then arrive at the final decision too weak

31
00:01:16,008 --> 00:01:17,426
to stop the machine?

32
00:01:18,346 --> 00:01:20,658
Challenger did not fail because the danger was

33
00:01:20,658 --> 00:01:23,647
invisible. It failed after a system learned how

34
00:01:23,647 --> 00:01:25,894
to keep flying with evidence that should have

35
00:01:25,894 --> 00:01:29,064
made flying harder. To understand how that happens,

36
00:01:29,064 --> 00:01:32,228
start with the promise the Shuttle system had

37
00:01:32,228 --> 00:01:35,495
to keep. Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo were built

38
00:01:35,495 --> 00:01:38,852
around singular missions. Dedicated hardware.

39
00:01:38,852 --> 00:01:42,037
Dedicated risk. Dedicated public attention.

40
00:01:42,879 --> 00:01:45,081
The Shuttle was designed to break that model.

41
00:01:45,861 --> 00:01:50,246
Reusable. Frequent. Routine. Less expedition,

42
00:01:50,246 --> 00:01:54,687
more airline. That promise shaped the organization

43
00:01:54,687 --> 00:01:57,480
around it. When a program promises routine,

44
00:01:57,480 --> 00:02:00,254
every delay starts to mean something different.

45
00:02:01,094 --> 00:02:04,122
A scrub is still an engineering decision,

46
00:02:04,122 --> 00:02:06,526
but it is also a schedule problem.

47
00:02:06,526 --> 00:02:09,019
A budget problem. A public problem.

48
00:02:09,019 --> 00:02:11,958
A problem that moves through contracts,

49
00:02:11,958 --> 00:02:15,965
payload windows, congressional expectations, and the

50
00:02:15,965 --> 00:02:17,835
reputation of the agency.

51
00:02:17,835 --> 00:02:21,563
NASA entered 1986 with an aggressive flight schedule

52
00:02:21,563 --> 00:02:24,229
and a system that had to justify itself

53
00:02:24,229 --> 00:02:28,104
through repetition. The Shuttle was not only a

54
00:02:28,104 --> 00:02:30,372
spacecraft. It was an operating model.

55
00:02:31,234 --> 00:02:34,053
The first thing to understand about Challenger is

56
00:02:34,053 --> 00:02:36,671
that the program was built to make spaceflight

57
00:02:36,671 --> 00:02:39,925
feel normal. Normal operation is useful.

58
00:02:40,687 --> 00:02:43,328
It is also dangerous when it teaches people

59
00:02:43,328 --> 00:02:46,776
to treat unresolved problems as background conditions.

60
00:02:47,092 --> 00:02:49,019
No one in this story needed to wake

61
00:02:49,019 --> 00:02:50,258
up wanting a disaster.

62
00:02:50,318 --> 00:02:53,204
That matters because the easy version turns the

63
00:02:53,204 --> 00:02:55,008
accident into a morality play.

64
00:02:55,889 --> 00:02:57,364
Bad people made bad choices,

65
00:02:57,364 --> 00:02:59,415
so better people would have stopped it.

66
00:03:00,337 --> 00:03:02,401
The record is harder than that.

67
00:03:02,669 --> 00:03:04,800
The system was full of people trying to

68
00:03:04,800 --> 00:03:07,397
do their jobs inside a decision structure that

69
00:03:07,397 --> 00:03:09,395
kept lowering the force of warnings.

70
00:03:10,236 --> 00:03:12,379
Three pressures were running at the same time.

71
00:03:13,300 --> 00:03:17,192
First: technical uncertainty. The Shuttle was

72
00:03:17,192 --> 00:03:21,404
enormously complex. Each flight produced new evidence

73
00:03:21,404 --> 00:03:24,494
about how hardware behaved in the real vehicle,

74
00:03:24,494 --> 00:03:26,634
under real loads, in real weather.

75
00:03:26,634 --> 00:03:29,305
That gap between design expectation and operating

76
00:03:29,305 --> 00:03:31,120
evidence is normal in engineering.

77
00:03:31,841 --> 00:03:33,924
What matters is how the gap gets handled.

78
00:03:35,004 --> 00:03:39,338
Second: schedule pressure. Delays did not move one

79
00:03:39,338 --> 00:03:40,510
item on one calendar.

80
00:03:41,111 --> 00:03:44,376
They shifted payloads, crews, customers,

81
00:03:44,376 --> 00:03:48,705
reviews, and promises. The cost of stopping was

82
00:03:48,705 --> 00:03:53,268
visible immediately. Third: institutional reputation.

83
00:03:54,250 --> 00:03:56,574
NASA was not only an engineering organization.

84
00:03:57,294 --> 00:03:58,989
It was a national symbol,

85
00:03:58,989 --> 00:04:01,532
a funding case, a Cold War instrument,

86
00:04:01,532 --> 00:04:02,804
and a public trust.

87
00:04:03,605 --> 00:04:06,150
These pressures met inside the same rooms.

88
00:04:06,871 --> 00:04:09,624
When they conflicted, the most flexible thing was

89
00:04:09,624 --> 00:04:12,936
often uncertainty. A technical concern could be

90
00:04:12,936 --> 00:04:15,605
reframed. It could be qualified.

91
00:04:15,605 --> 00:04:17,408
It could be moved to the next review.

92
00:04:18,110 --> 00:04:20,435
Schedule and reputation were harder to bend.

93
00:04:21,276 --> 00:04:23,040
So the practical standard drifted.

94
00:04:23,079 --> 00:04:26,779
The question became: keep flying unless the evidence

95
00:04:26,779 --> 00:04:29,050
against flying is overwhelming.

96
00:04:29,091 --> 00:04:31,013
That is very different from:

97
00:04:31,013 --> 00:04:33,855
do not fly unless the evidence for safety

98
00:04:33,855 --> 00:04:37,815
is clear. The difference showed up most clearly

99
00:04:37,815 --> 00:04:40,203
in one component. The Shuttle used two solid

100
00:04:40,203 --> 00:04:42,647
rocket boosters for most of its thrust during

101
00:04:42,647 --> 00:04:44,319
the first two minutes of flight.

102
00:04:45,259 --> 00:04:47,730
Each booster was not built as one continuous

103
00:04:47,730 --> 00:04:51,731
piece. It was assembled from cylindrical segments,

104
00:04:51,731 --> 00:04:54,216
stacked and joined at the launch site.

105
00:04:54,216 --> 00:04:56,578
Where the segments met, there was a field

106
00:04:56,578 --> 00:05:00,300
joint. Inside that joint, two rubber O-rings,

107
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:02,106
a primary and a secondary,

108
00:05:02,106 --> 00:05:04,771
were supposed to seal the gap and keep

109
00:05:04,771 --> 00:05:07,694
hot combustion gases inside the booster.

110
00:05:08,557 --> 00:05:10,079
The joint had to seal quickly.

111
00:05:10,779 --> 00:05:13,125
Pressure inside the motor could distort the metal

112
00:05:13,125 --> 00:05:16,118
parts at ignition. The O-rings had to move

113
00:05:16,118 --> 00:05:18,788
into position fast enough to block hot gas

114
00:05:18,788 --> 00:05:21,613
before it escaped. Cold mattered because rubber does

115
00:05:21,613 --> 00:05:23,137
not respond the same way in cold.

116
00:05:24,038 --> 00:05:26,140
A seal that moves quickly when warm can

117
00:05:26,140 --> 00:05:27,783
respond more slowly when cold.

118
00:05:28,545 --> 00:05:31,528
In this joint, timing was not a detail.

119
00:05:32,329 --> 00:05:34,432
Timing was the safety margin.

120
00:05:35,254 --> 00:05:38,113
If the seals failed, there was no graceful

121
00:05:38,113 --> 00:05:41,738
backup. Hot gas could burn through the booster

122
00:05:41,738 --> 00:05:45,094
casing, reach surrounding structure, and turn a local

123
00:05:45,094 --> 00:05:46,848
leak into a vehicle failure.

124
00:05:47,048 --> 00:05:49,383
The O-ring problem had been showing itself before

125
00:05:49,383 --> 00:05:53,019
Challenger. Post-flight inspections found erosion on

126
00:05:53,019 --> 00:05:55,422
the primary seal. In some cases,

127
00:05:55,422 --> 00:05:57,693
gas had blown past it and left evidence

128
00:05:57,693 --> 00:05:58,829
deeper in the joint.

129
00:05:59,831 --> 00:06:01,435
Engineers documented the damage.

130
00:06:02,036 --> 00:06:04,079
They measured it. They reported it.

131
00:06:04,880 --> 00:06:07,386
The dangerous part is what happened next.

132
00:06:07,687 --> 00:06:11,067
Because the missions succeeded, because the vehicles

133
00:06:11,067 --> 00:06:14,140
came home, damage could be processed as evidence

134
00:06:14,140 --> 00:06:16,983
that the system had tolerated the condition.

135
00:06:17,002 --> 00:06:20,181
A damaged component in a surviving system can

136
00:06:20,181 --> 00:06:21,269
be read two ways.

137
00:06:22,252 --> 00:06:25,035
One reading says: we were closer to failure

138
00:06:25,035 --> 00:06:26,625
than we should have been,

139
00:06:26,625 --> 00:06:29,169
so we stop and fix the condition before

140
00:06:29,169 --> 00:06:30,974
we repeat it. The other says:

141
00:06:30,974 --> 00:06:33,635
the vehicle survived, the margin held,

142
00:06:33,635 --> 00:06:36,896
and the risk can be carried while improvement

143
00:06:36,896 --> 00:06:40,756
work continues. The second reading became easier each

144
00:06:40,756 --> 00:06:42,355
time the Shuttle flew and returned.

145
00:06:43,036 --> 00:06:45,788
What had started as a serious anomaly gradually

146
00:06:45,788 --> 00:06:47,920
became part of the operating history.

147
00:06:48,601 --> 00:06:50,504
The O-ring warning did not disappear.

148
00:06:51,324 --> 00:06:54,397
It moved. That is how a warning can

149
00:06:54,397 --> 00:06:56,816
die inside a large organization.

150
00:06:56,816 --> 00:06:59,951
Not through silence. Through translation.

151
00:06:59,951 --> 00:07:02,718
It starts when an engineer sees something wrong.

152
00:07:03,459 --> 00:07:04,843
The data is specific.

153
00:07:05,444 --> 00:07:06,747
The language is uncomfortable.

154
00:07:07,369 --> 00:07:10,136
Erosion. Blow-by. Heat effects.

155
00:07:10,877 --> 00:07:12,664
A seal that did not behave the way

156
00:07:12,664 --> 00:07:17,232
the design assumed. Precise evidence has force.

157
00:07:17,232 --> 00:07:19,454
Then the evidence becomes a discussion item.

158
00:07:20,175 --> 00:07:22,974
It enters a meeting with dozens of other

159
00:07:22,974 --> 00:07:25,858
concerns. Other anomalies. Other systems.

160
00:07:25,858 --> 00:07:30,473
Other deadlines. The context broadens and the urgency

161
00:07:30,473 --> 00:07:33,851
flattens. From there, the discussion becomes a

162
00:07:33,851 --> 00:07:37,600
judgment call. Does this affect the next flight?

163
00:07:37,600 --> 00:07:39,921
The answer depends on the question the room

164
00:07:39,921 --> 00:07:42,501
decides to ask. If the question is,

165
00:07:42,501 --> 00:07:44,646
can we prove this will cause a failure,

166
00:07:45,288 --> 00:07:46,509
the answer is usually no.

167
00:07:47,370 --> 00:07:50,050
Predicting a specific loss on a specific flight

168
00:07:50,050 --> 00:07:52,324
is hard. If the question is,

169
00:07:52,324 --> 00:07:54,177
can we prove this will not fail,

170
00:07:54,737 --> 00:07:55,958
the answer is also no.

171
00:07:56,738 --> 00:07:59,000
But the first question keeps the schedule alive.

172
00:07:59,961 --> 00:08:02,625
Then the judgment becomes a schedule decision.

173
00:08:02,625 --> 00:08:04,146
The language changes again.

174
00:08:04,968 --> 00:08:07,452
It is no longer mainly about erosion depth

175
00:08:07,452 --> 00:08:10,355
or sealing time. It is about whether there

176
00:08:10,355 --> 00:08:11,499
is enough cause to delay.

177
00:08:12,519 --> 00:08:13,802
Delay has a phone tree.

178
00:08:14,442 --> 00:08:17,487
Delay has cost. Delay has a visible owner.

179
00:08:18,490 --> 00:08:21,841
If the flight succeeds, the decision becomes

180
00:08:21,841 --> 00:08:24,438
precedent. We flew with that condition and came

181
00:08:24,438 --> 00:08:27,491
back. That fact starts to compete with the

182
00:08:27,491 --> 00:08:28,786
warning that preceded it.

183
00:08:29,548 --> 00:08:31,891
This route ran more than once before Challenger.

184
00:08:32,653 --> 00:08:34,722
Each pass made the next one easier to

185
00:08:34,722 --> 00:08:38,047
defend. Engineers were not simply ignored.

186
00:08:38,047 --> 00:08:40,593
They were often heard, then absorbed into a

187
00:08:40,593 --> 00:08:43,212
process that had learned how to carry their

188
00:08:43,212 --> 00:08:46,423
concern without stopping. Months before Challenger,

189
00:08:46,423 --> 00:08:49,462
Roger Boisjoly warned that a similar field-joint

190
00:08:49,462 --> 00:08:52,500
problem could lead to catastrophe of the highest

191
00:08:52,500 --> 00:08:54,205
order and loss of human life.

192
00:08:55,306 --> 00:08:57,469
That memo did not come from hindsight.

193
00:08:58,309 --> 00:09:00,454
It came from inside the system,

194
00:09:00,454 --> 00:09:03,714
before the accident, from an engineer close to

195
00:09:03,714 --> 00:09:07,172
the hardware. The temperature pattern also had more

196
00:09:07,172 --> 00:09:09,412
weight than the launch-night argument made it feel.

197
00:09:10,212 --> 00:09:12,648
When the full flight history was framed one

198
00:09:12,648 --> 00:09:15,422
way, the cold-weather signal could look debatable.

199
00:09:16,482 --> 00:09:19,552
When the full record was framed another way,

200
00:09:19,552 --> 00:09:23,134
cold O-ring distress became much harder to dismiss.

201
00:09:24,015 --> 00:09:27,150
A chart can contain real information and still

202
00:09:27,150 --> 00:09:29,884
weaken the warning if it frames the wrong

203
00:09:29,884 --> 00:09:32,924
question. Richard Feynman's later appendix named the

204
00:09:32,924 --> 00:09:36,401
broader danger plainly: previous success can become

205
00:09:36,401 --> 00:09:39,754
misleading evidence. A survived flight can show that

206
00:09:39,754 --> 00:09:40,792
the vehicle got through.

207
00:09:40,812 --> 00:09:43,666
It does not prove the risk was safe

208
00:09:43,666 --> 00:09:46,257
to repeat. By January 1986,

209
00:09:46,257 --> 00:09:49,230
Challenger was not facing a new problem.

210
00:09:49,991 --> 00:09:52,073
The program had evidence of O-ring distress.

211
00:09:52,794 --> 00:09:53,995
It had temperature concern.

212
00:09:54,636 --> 00:09:56,678
It had waivers. It had memos.

213
00:09:57,259 --> 00:09:59,120
It had a known field-joint problem.

214
00:09:59,782 --> 00:10:02,255
It had a launch system that kept treating

215
00:10:02,255 --> 00:10:04,365
survival as part of the safety case.

216
00:10:04,385 --> 00:10:06,466
Then the weather turned that old problem into

217
00:10:06,466 --> 00:10:10,195
a launch decision. January 27,

218
00:10:10,195 --> 00:10:14,602
1986. Less than twenty-four hours before the scheduled

219
00:10:14,602 --> 00:10:17,994
launch. A teleconference connected NASA's Marshall

220
00:10:17,994 --> 00:10:20,597
Space Flight Center, Kennedy Space Center,

221
00:10:20,597 --> 00:10:23,645
and Morton Thiokol, the contractor that built the

222
00:10:23,645 --> 00:10:28,083
solid rocket boosters. The subject was temperature.

223
00:10:29,044 --> 00:10:32,299
Forecasts and engineering estimates pointed to launch

224
00:10:32,299 --> 00:10:35,416
conditions far colder than prior Shuttle experience.

225
00:10:35,436 --> 00:10:38,672
The launch temperature would be about 36 degrees

226
00:10:38,672 --> 00:10:42,214
Fahrenheit. The right aft field joint was estimated

227
00:10:42,214 --> 00:10:44,817
colder, around 28 degrees Fahrenheit,

228
00:10:44,817 --> 00:10:46,413
plus or minus five degrees.

229
00:10:47,274 --> 00:10:50,058
Thiokol engineers were concerned because cold could

230
00:10:50,058 --> 00:10:52,100
slow the O-rings at the exact moment they

231
00:10:52,100 --> 00:10:55,427
needed to seal. Their recommendation was clear:

232
00:10:56,248 --> 00:10:59,432
do not launch below 53 degrees Fahrenheit.

233
00:11:00,153 --> 00:11:02,620
That number mattered because it was tied to

234
00:11:02,620 --> 00:11:05,635
the lowest relevant prior experience they believed

235
00:11:05,635 --> 00:11:08,580
they could defend. NASA managers pushed back.

236
00:11:09,320 --> 00:11:12,323
In a technical review, pushback can be necessary.

237
00:11:13,164 --> 00:11:15,032
The danger was the standard that began to

238
00:11:15,032 --> 00:11:17,708
govern the room. The question drifted.

239
00:11:18,691 --> 00:11:21,668
Show that this is safe to fly became

240
00:11:21,668 --> 00:11:23,174
prove that it will fail.

241
00:11:24,196 --> 00:11:26,239
That shift reversed the burden of proof.

242
00:11:27,240 --> 00:11:30,322
Instead of requiring evidence that launch was safe,

243
00:11:30,322 --> 00:11:32,893
the process demanded evidence that failure was

244
00:11:32,893 --> 00:11:36,638
certain. Engineering evidence usually does not arrive

245
00:11:36,638 --> 00:11:39,698
that way. It arrives as a missing margin,

246
00:11:39,698 --> 00:11:43,048
a condition outside experience, a trend with enough

247
00:11:43,048 --> 00:11:46,321
signal to matter before the catastrophe supplies

248
00:11:46,321 --> 00:11:50,184
certainty. The engineers had evidence of risk.

249
00:11:50,205 --> 00:11:52,111
They did not have an equation that converted

250
00:11:52,111 --> 00:11:54,068
temperature into guaranteed loss of vehicle.

251
00:11:54,710 --> 00:11:57,373
That absence became useful to the launch case.

252
00:11:57,373 --> 00:11:59,937
Thiokol asked for an offline caucus.

253
00:12:00,677 --> 00:12:02,792
The caucus lasted far longer than the five

254
00:12:02,792 --> 00:12:05,767
minutes first requested. When they returned,

255
00:12:05,767 --> 00:12:07,465
the recommendation had changed.

256
00:12:08,205 --> 00:12:09,892
The new position was that the data was

257
00:12:09,892 --> 00:12:11,688
inconclusive and launch could proceed.

258
00:12:11,729 --> 00:12:13,870
The cold had not changed.

259
00:12:14,432 --> 00:12:16,153
The joint had not changed.

260
00:12:16,793 --> 00:12:18,596
The limits of the data had not changed.

261
00:12:19,255 --> 00:12:20,677
The decision frame changed.

262
00:12:21,578 --> 00:12:24,759
One instruction from that caucus still carries the

263
00:12:24,759 --> 00:12:25,942
shape of the moment.

264
00:12:26,192 --> 00:12:28,320
Jerry Mason told Bob Lund to take off

265
00:12:28,320 --> 00:12:31,016
his engineering hat and put on his management

266
00:12:31,016 --> 00:12:34,057
hat. No single phrase explains the disaster.

267
00:12:34,097 --> 00:12:37,047
No single person explains it either.

268
00:12:37,465 --> 00:12:39,872
The deeper fact is that the same process

269
00:12:39,872 --> 00:12:43,299
could take a specific engineering objection and return

270
00:12:43,299 --> 00:12:46,216
a launch recommendation from the same evidence.

271
00:12:46,897 --> 00:12:49,038
The launch-eve reversal is dramatic,

272
00:12:49,038 --> 00:12:50,822
but it is not the whole failure.

273
00:12:51,582 --> 00:12:54,246
A warning also has to travel.

274
00:12:54,967 --> 00:12:57,927
It has to move from hardware to engineers,

275
00:12:57,927 --> 00:13:01,758
from engineers to managers, from contractors to NASA,

276
00:13:01,758 --> 00:13:04,892
from lower review levels to the people with

277
00:13:04,892 --> 00:13:06,982
authority to stop the launch.

278
00:13:06,982 --> 00:13:09,544
At each step, the signal can be compressed.

279
00:13:10,426 --> 00:13:12,916
Compression is normal in large programs.

280
00:13:12,916 --> 00:13:16,286
But when compression changes an active objection into

281
00:13:16,286 --> 00:13:18,483
a resolved item, the system has made a

282
00:13:18,483 --> 00:13:20,754
decision without naming it directly.

283
00:13:21,535 --> 00:13:23,138
Safety should have been a backstop.

284
00:13:23,857 --> 00:13:26,698
The Commission later criticized weak problem

285
00:13:26,698 --> 00:13:30,049
reporting, inadequate trend analysis, misrepresented

286
00:13:30,049 --> 00:13:33,255
criticality, and safety structures that did not give

287
00:13:33,255 --> 00:13:36,533
the concern enough independent force at the decisive

288
00:13:36,533 --> 00:13:39,758
points. People can care about safety while the

289
00:13:39,758 --> 00:13:42,917
way decisions are made still lets a warning

290
00:13:42,917 --> 00:13:44,672
arrive too late, too thin,

291
00:13:44,672 --> 00:13:47,041
or too resolved to change action.

292
00:13:48,142 --> 00:13:52,069
By launch morning, the warning had passed through

293
00:13:52,069 --> 00:13:55,901
hardware evidence, paperwork, meetings, waivers,

294
00:13:55,901 --> 00:13:59,637
charts, recommendation, caucus, and management

295
00:13:59,637 --> 00:14:02,259
acceptance. At the end of that route,

296
00:14:02,259 --> 00:14:03,817
launch was still open.

297
00:14:04,101 --> 00:14:10,003
At 11:38 a.m. Eastern Standard Time on January

298
00:14:10,003 --> 00:14:14,104
28, 1986, Challenger launched from Kennedy Space

299
00:14:14,104 --> 00:14:16,767
Center. Within the first second,

300
00:14:16,767 --> 00:14:19,576
smoke appeared near the right aft field joint.

301
00:14:20,297 --> 00:14:22,406
The primary O-ring had not sealed the way

302
00:14:22,406 --> 00:14:23,301
it needed to seal.

303
00:14:24,121 --> 00:14:27,159
The secondary O-ring, affected by cold and joint

304
00:14:27,159 --> 00:14:29,730
movement, had not saved the joint in time.

305
00:14:30,591 --> 00:14:32,948
The smoke continued through roughly T plus two

306
00:14:32,948 --> 00:14:33,855
and a half seconds.

307
00:14:34,635 --> 00:14:38,024
Then it disappeared. The Commission considered that

308
00:14:38,024 --> 00:14:40,770
combustion residue may have temporarily sealed the

309
00:14:40,770 --> 00:14:42,117
breach. For a short time,

310
00:14:42,117 --> 00:14:44,858
the vehicle could look normal while the failure

311
00:14:44,858 --> 00:14:48,751
chain remained alive. That temporary quiet is one

312
00:14:48,751 --> 00:14:51,119
of the clearest details in the record.

313
00:14:52,100 --> 00:14:54,509
The physical system did what the organization had

314
00:14:54,509 --> 00:14:57,565
been doing for years: a sign of breach

315
00:14:57,565 --> 00:15:01,093
appeared, an explanation arrived, and flight

316
00:15:01,093 --> 00:15:04,578
continued. Around 58 to 59 seconds into flight,

317
00:15:04,578 --> 00:15:06,676
flame became visible again.

318
00:15:06,696 --> 00:15:09,632
Hot gas from the right booster began damaging

319
00:15:09,632 --> 00:15:13,032
surrounding structure, including the External Tank

320
00:15:13,032 --> 00:15:16,267
area. At approximately seventy-three seconds,

321
00:15:16,267 --> 00:15:20,709
Challenger broke apart. Francis "Dick" Scobee,

322
00:15:20,709 --> 00:15:25,202
Michael Smith, Judith Resnik, Ellison Onizuka,

323
00:15:25,202 --> 00:15:30,155
Ronald McNair, Gregory Jarvis, and Christa McAuliffe

324
00:15:30,155 --> 00:15:33,333
were lost. The visible failure lasted seconds.

325
00:15:34,115 --> 00:15:36,578
The invisible one had been accumulating for years.

326
00:15:37,500 --> 00:15:40,436
What came next was the question every institution

327
00:15:40,436 --> 00:15:43,300
fears: how did this happen when the evidence

328
00:15:43,300 --> 00:15:47,229
already existed? President Reagan appointed the Rogers

329
00:15:47,229 --> 00:15:49,340
Commission, chaired by William Rogers.

330
00:15:50,381 --> 00:15:52,586
Richard Feynman was one of its members,

331
00:15:52,586 --> 00:15:55,066
and his independent work became part of the

332
00:15:55,066 --> 00:15:57,133
public memory of the investigation.

333
00:15:57,518 --> 00:15:59,722
The physical cause was direct:

334
00:15:59,722 --> 00:16:02,720
failure of the seal in the right booster's

335
00:16:02,720 --> 00:16:05,101
aft field joint, hot gas escaping,

336
00:16:05,101 --> 00:16:07,482
damage to the External Tank area,

337
00:16:07,482 --> 00:16:11,639
and vehicle breakup. The Commission did not stop

338
00:16:11,639 --> 00:16:13,029
at the physical cause.

339
00:16:13,029 --> 00:16:15,832
It found a flawed launch decision process.

340
00:16:16,594 --> 00:16:18,056
It found communication failures.

341
00:16:18,836 --> 00:16:21,750
It found that crucial information about O-ring

342
00:16:21,750 --> 00:16:24,588
history, temperature concern, and continuing

343
00:16:24,588 --> 00:16:27,203
engineering opposition did not reach key

344
00:16:27,203 --> 00:16:30,490
decision-makers with the force and clarity it needed.

345
00:16:30,510 --> 00:16:33,812
The people closest to the hardware had the

346
00:16:33,812 --> 00:16:36,076
sharpest version of the risk.

347
00:16:36,096 --> 00:16:38,786
The people with the authority to stop launch

348
00:16:38,786 --> 00:16:40,822
received a softened version of it.

349
00:16:40,955 --> 00:16:43,901
The Commission described the immediate failure:

350
00:16:43,901 --> 00:16:45,768
the part, the launch decision,

351
00:16:45,768 --> 00:16:48,642
and the communication system that softened the

352
00:16:48,642 --> 00:16:52,928
warning. Diane Vaughan later named the larger pattern:

353
00:16:52,928 --> 00:16:54,873
the normalization of deviance.

354
00:16:55,833 --> 00:16:58,633
A deviation from expected performance becomes normal

355
00:16:58,633 --> 00:17:00,581
because the system keeps surviving it.

356
00:17:01,501 --> 00:17:03,640
The phrase is useful because it does not

357
00:17:03,640 --> 00:17:07,352
require a conspiracy. It describes a slow adjustment

358
00:17:07,352 --> 00:17:09,392
in what feels acceptable.

359
00:17:09,727 --> 00:17:12,653
The line moves because each previous crossing did

360
00:17:12,653 --> 00:17:13,977
not end in catastrophe.

361
00:17:14,940 --> 00:17:17,938
Challenger is taught in engineering programs,

362
00:17:17,938 --> 00:17:21,551
business schools, and organizational behavior courses

363
00:17:21,551 --> 00:17:24,241
because the pattern is not limited to NASA.

364
00:17:24,458 --> 00:17:28,084
Repeated near-misses create false confidence.

365
00:17:28,104 --> 00:17:31,333
Every time a system survives a close call,

366
00:17:31,333 --> 00:17:33,233
perceived risk can drop.

367
00:17:33,974 --> 00:17:36,697
The near-miss gets counted as validation instead of

368
00:17:36,697 --> 00:17:39,964
warning. Missing data gets mistaken for safety.

369
00:17:40,846 --> 00:17:43,251
No evidence of failure is not the same

370
00:17:43,251 --> 00:17:44,880
as evidence of no failure,

371
00:17:44,880 --> 00:17:48,525
especially when the dangerous condition has not really

372
00:17:48,525 --> 00:17:52,363
been tested. Schedule pressure changes proof standards

373
00:17:52,363 --> 00:17:55,028
quietly. No one has to announce that the

374
00:17:55,028 --> 00:17:57,610
bar has moved. The bar for stopping can

375
00:17:57,610 --> 00:18:00,443
rise inch by inch until only certainty of

376
00:18:00,443 --> 00:18:04,603
disaster justifies delay. Institutions reward

377
00:18:04,603 --> 00:18:08,508
continuity over interruption. The person who keeps the

378
00:18:08,508 --> 00:18:10,796
line moving is easier to celebrate than the

379
00:18:10,796 --> 00:18:12,575
person who stops it for a risk that

380
00:18:12,575 --> 00:18:14,037
might never become visible.

381
00:18:15,039 --> 00:18:16,765
Anomalies become background noise.

382
00:18:17,547 --> 00:18:20,307
The first time something unexpected happens,

383
00:18:20,307 --> 00:18:22,644
it gets attention. The fifth time,

384
00:18:22,644 --> 00:18:26,053
a tracking number. The tenth time,

385
00:18:26,053 --> 00:18:29,120
it starts to sound like how the system

386
00:18:29,120 --> 00:18:32,289
works. These behaviors appear wherever the cost of

387
00:18:32,289 --> 00:18:35,232
stopping is immediate and the cost of continuing

388
00:18:35,232 --> 00:18:38,972
is statistical. Healthcare systems.

389
00:18:38,972 --> 00:18:43,317
Financial systems. Infrastructure. Software.

390
00:18:43,317 --> 00:18:45,933
Any organization that has to decide whether a

391
00:18:45,933 --> 00:18:48,707
warning is strong enough to interrupt momentum.

392
00:18:49,689 --> 00:18:51,551
Challenger did not invent this pattern.

393
00:18:52,313 --> 00:18:53,515
It made the pattern visible.

394
00:18:54,416 --> 00:18:56,921
Disasters rarely begin at the moment of impact.

395
00:18:57,662 --> 00:19:00,142
They begin when a system gets used to

396
00:19:00,142 --> 00:19:03,365
explaining away what it should have stopped to

397
00:19:03,365 --> 00:19:05,841
understand. Challenger was a long sequence of

398
00:19:05,841 --> 00:19:08,700
accommodations, each one easier to defend than the

399
00:19:08,700 --> 00:19:09,820
whole chain would have been.

400
00:19:10,821 --> 00:19:12,159
The smoke at T plus zero point six

401
00:19:12,159 --> 00:19:14,282
seven eight seconds is why the story should

402
00:19:14,282 --> 00:19:16,128
not start with the explosion.

403
00:19:17,089 --> 00:19:19,113
The first visible warning was small.

404
00:19:19,953 --> 00:19:22,239
Then it vanished. For a while,

405
00:19:22,239 --> 00:19:25,740
everything looked normal. The same thing had already

406
00:19:25,740 --> 00:19:27,084
happened inside the organization.

407
00:19:28,045 --> 00:19:30,709
A warning appeared. The system explained it.

408
00:19:31,288 --> 00:19:34,268
The launch continued. That is why the next

409
00:19:34,268 --> 00:19:36,017
case belongs beside Challenger.

410
00:19:36,017 --> 00:19:39,162
Therac-25 is not another space story.

411
00:19:39,883 --> 00:19:41,138
It is a smaller room,

412
00:19:41,138 --> 00:19:43,725
a medical machine, a software interface,

413
00:19:43,725 --> 00:19:47,097
and operators trying to explain errors the machine

414
00:19:47,097 --> 00:19:48,979
was not built to make visible.

415
00:19:48,979 --> 00:19:51,791
The form changes. The pattern does not:

416
00:19:52,515 --> 00:19:54,945
confidence moves faster than verification.

417
00:19:56,030 --> 00:20:00,230
Next time: Therac-25, a medical machine that exposed

418
00:20:00,230 --> 00:20:03,685
what happens when software confidence outruns the

419
00:20:03,685 --> 00:20:05,162
evidence users can see.
